WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.660 --> 00:00:01.640
PETER NORVIG: All right.

00:00:01.640 --> 00:00:02.890
Welcome, everybody.

00:00:04.850 --> 00:00:07.300
So I'm going to talk about
online education.

00:00:07.300 --> 00:00:10.720
And so I'm an engineer
at Google,

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:12.110
but I'm also an educator.

00:00:12.110 --> 00:00:16.320
And here I am in the classroom
at Stanford University

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:19.170
teaching artificial
intelligence.

00:00:19.170 --> 00:00:22.290
And when I taught this class, I
felt like the subject matter

00:00:22.290 --> 00:00:23.980
was pretty advanced
and up to date.

00:00:23.980 --> 00:00:25.710
We tried to make it that way.

00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:28.570
But I also felt like the
delivery mechanism hadn't

00:00:28.570 --> 00:00:32.920
really changed very much
since the 14th century.

00:00:32.920 --> 00:00:35.200
This is the University of
Bologna, the very first

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:36.440
university.

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:42.240
And you see we got the sage on
the stage, just like today.

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:45.330
We got the textbook.

00:00:45.330 --> 00:00:48.500
And we got the sleeping
guy in the back.

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:52.160
And my class at Stanford was
at 9:00 AM, so I'm very

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:54.250
familiar with that phenomenon.

00:00:54.250 --> 00:00:57.250
Now, over the years, there
have been technological

00:00:57.250 --> 00:00:59.290
advances since those days.

00:00:59.290 --> 00:01:02.710
And so let's jump ahead
to the modern era.

00:01:02.710 --> 00:01:05.830
By modern era, I mean 1791.

00:01:05.830 --> 00:01:10.540
And "Life of Johnson." Boswell
was writing, "Lectures were

00:01:10.540 --> 00:01:13.800
once useful, but now, when all
can read, and books so

00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:16.760
numerous, lectures
are unnecessary.

00:01:16.760 --> 00:01:18.630
If your attention fails
and you miss part of a

00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:19.600
lecture, it's lost.

00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:23.330
You cannot go back as
you do upon a book."

00:01:23.330 --> 00:01:26.000
Now, of course, that's true.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:27.040
He makes a good point.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:29.590
Of course, now we do have the
ability to go back with the

00:01:29.590 --> 00:01:30.935
little scroller in YouTube.

00:01:30.935 --> 00:01:33.850
He hadn't anticipated that.

00:01:33.850 --> 00:01:35.910
But it's still true that there's
a lot of things about

00:01:35.910 --> 00:01:40.350
a book that are better
than a lecture.

00:01:40.350 --> 00:01:43.600
And so I've done lecturing,
but I've also done a book.

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:45.310
And I began to think
about that.

00:01:45.310 --> 00:01:49.760
And here's a passage
from my textbook.

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:52.750
And this is one that my
co-author Stuart Russell did

00:01:52.750 --> 00:01:53.540
the first draft.

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:54.430
And I said well,
wait a minute.

00:01:54.430 --> 00:01:55.200
That's not quite right.

00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:56.560
And then I did a draft.

00:01:56.560 --> 00:01:58.860
And then I wasn't convinced
that was right either.

00:01:58.860 --> 00:02:00.720
And we had to choose what
to put in the book.

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:02.610
You're only allowed to
put one thing in.

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:05.090
And we realized we are the two
worst guys in the world to

00:02:05.090 --> 00:02:06.350
make that choice.

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:09.160
Because it's been a long time
since we were confused about

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:10.169
this subject.

00:02:10.169 --> 00:02:13.030
But we know that the people
who would be the best at

00:02:13.030 --> 00:02:15.500
making that choice are out
there, but we just lost the

00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:16.200
feedback loop.

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:18.440
We know that there are students
who are buying the

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:22.530
book and taking out their magic
marker and highlighting

00:02:22.530 --> 00:02:24.030
the important stuff.

00:02:24.030 --> 00:02:25.860
And maybe they have a different
color to highlight

00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:28.220
the confusing stuff that
they didn't understand.

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:30.220
And they're writing notes
in the margin, and

00:02:30.220 --> 00:02:31.360
we're losing all that.

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:33.510
And so we said, well, if we can
close the loop and bring

00:02:33.510 --> 00:02:35.430
that online, then maybe
we can get that back.

00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:39.200
And we can have rapid
improvement in textbooks.

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:42.220
Here's another diagram
out of the Book.

00:02:42.220 --> 00:02:44.270
And it took me a long time
to produce this.

00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:46.960
I had to write a program to
munch the data, and then draw

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:47.920
the 3D plot.

00:02:47.920 --> 00:02:50.450
And then I rotated the
3D plot until I got

00:02:50.450 --> 00:02:51.900
just the right viewpoint.

00:02:51.900 --> 00:02:55.720
And then, the poor student just
gets these raw pixels and

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:58.570
doesn't get the learning
experience that I got from

00:02:58.570 --> 00:02:59.640
manipulating it.

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:01.620
But I know that there are
techniques where you can have

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:05.220
all this stuff be running live
and the student could get the

00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:07.310
same experience I had.

00:03:07.310 --> 00:03:13.180
So Hal Abelson, a famous
educator from MIT, was

00:03:13.180 --> 00:03:14.240
visiting Google.

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:17.630
And I asked Hal, I'm interested
in kind of the

00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:18.700
theory of learning.

00:03:18.700 --> 00:03:21.370
What do I have to learn
to get up to date?

00:03:21.370 --> 00:03:23.530
And I expected him to
give me an answer of

00:03:23.530 --> 00:03:25.190
a big pile of books.

00:03:25.190 --> 00:03:28.450
And instead, I got the best
answer I've ever gotten, which

00:03:28.450 --> 00:03:31.690
was he said you only have
to read one paper.

00:03:31.690 --> 00:03:35.220
And that's Benjamin Bloom's
paper from 1984 on what bloom

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:37.280
calls the 2 sigma effect--

00:03:37.280 --> 00:03:38.860
2 standard deviations.

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:43.490
And Bloom says, if you do
one-on-one tutoring and you do

00:03:43.490 --> 00:03:47.320
mastery learning, which means
you keep teaching until the

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:49.940
student actually guess it,
rather than until the date of

00:03:49.940 --> 00:03:53.510
the scheduled exam, then you
get two standard deviations

00:03:53.510 --> 00:03:55.470
improvement on average.

00:03:55.470 --> 00:03:57.720
And so you see the
chart moves over.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:01.710
And if you look at the midpoint
there, it means 98%

00:04:01.710 --> 00:04:02.490
are above average.

00:04:02.490 --> 00:04:04.420
Almost like [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:04.420 --> 00:04:06.050
Now, we'll see a little bit
later that maybe he was

00:04:06.050 --> 00:04:08.710
exaggerating a little and not
all the experiments backup

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:11.270
exactly that amount
of improvement.

00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:13.440
But the improvement is there.

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:15.550
And this struck home, and it
seems to make a lot of sense.

00:04:15.550 --> 00:04:18.519
So one-on-one tutoring seems
like a powerful thing.

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:21.470
I think back in my life,
here I am with my

00:04:21.470 --> 00:04:22.990
first tutor, my mom.

00:04:22.990 --> 00:04:26.150
And we're going one-on-one and
I'm learning something there.

00:04:26.150 --> 00:04:29.270
So I said, can we take that
to the rest of the world?

00:04:29.270 --> 00:04:32.360
But I don't really have the time
or transportation to meet

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:34.370
with everybody one-on-one.

00:04:34.370 --> 00:04:38.340
So can I get close to it
by going one-on-many?

00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:41.660
So I began to try to teach in
that way, teaching not to one

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:44.890
student at a time but teaching
to one video

00:04:44.890 --> 00:04:46.850
recorder at a time.

00:04:46.850 --> 00:04:50.150
And then, interspersing the rest
of the lessons with it.

00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:54.640
So my co-teacher Sebastian Thrun
and I said, it's our

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:57.000
turn again to teach this
class at Stanford.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:58.950
This time, instead of just doing
it in the classroom,

00:04:58.950 --> 00:05:00.520
we're also going to
do it online.

00:05:00.520 --> 00:05:02.130
And we're going to offer
it to anybody in the

00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:04.110
world to sign up for.

00:05:04.110 --> 00:05:07.820
And 160,000 people
took us up on it.

00:05:07.820 --> 00:05:10.810
And since then, there have been
others that are doing

00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:11.740
this as well.

00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:16.070
So Coursera is one of the
well-known providers; Udacity,

00:05:16.070 --> 00:05:20.400
edX, this partnership of MIT
and Harvard, and now other

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:21.920
universities.

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:26.230
And at Google, we wanted
to get into it, too.

00:05:26.230 --> 00:05:28.890
And the first class we produced
was with Dan Russell.

00:05:28.890 --> 00:05:30.920
It was a class called Power
Searching with Google.

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:34.740
It just taught you how
to use Google better.

00:05:34.740 --> 00:05:37.510
And that worked so well we were
able to throw together a

00:05:37.510 --> 00:05:38.360
system to do that.

00:05:38.360 --> 00:05:39.970
Some of the people taking
and liked it.

00:05:39.970 --> 00:05:41.330
Thank you.

00:05:41.330 --> 00:05:44.110
That we said, well, why don't
we take the system that we

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:47.160
used to build this, and then
clean it up a little bit and

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:49.130
open source it and let
everybody use it?

00:05:49.130 --> 00:05:50.010
So that's what we did.

00:05:50.010 --> 00:05:52.380
We called it Course Builder.

00:05:52.380 --> 00:05:57.320
And last week, we had
the 1.4 launch.

00:05:57.320 --> 00:05:59.760
So we're iterating
through this.

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:01.680
There's the URL.

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:03.380
You can just search for
Course Builder or you

00:06:03.380 --> 00:06:04.330
can remember that.

00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:05.668
It's on code,google.com.

00:06:05.668 --> 00:06:09.950
And afterwards, we have five
laptops set up here down in

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:12.250
front and you can come
play with it.

00:06:12.250 --> 00:06:15.660
Or you can do it on your
own with the URL.

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:18.270
And here are some of the
technologies, the Google

00:06:18.270 --> 00:06:20.250
technologies, that we're
integrating.

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:22.210
So it runs on App Engine.

00:06:22.210 --> 00:06:27.980
It's not a Google service, it's
an open source product

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:30.550
that happens to run on a Google
service, App Engine.

00:06:30.550 --> 00:06:31.720
So you download it.

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:34.850
You get your own App Engine
instance and you run it.

00:06:34.850 --> 00:06:38.460
And you can integrate the
YouTube and the Docs and

00:06:38.460 --> 00:06:41.450
Hangouts and Groups and Gmail
and Account Login and

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:43.110
everything else.

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:46.020
And we got a couple dozen
different courses up and

00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:49.400
running now from different
universities and nonprofits.

00:06:49.400 --> 00:06:51.840
And more on the way.

00:06:51.840 --> 00:06:54.450
Here's one example
from saylor.org.

00:06:54.450 --> 00:06:57.380
It's a nonprofit that's doing
a bunch of different

00:06:57.380 --> 00:06:59.260
courses with us.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:02.840
We just announced this week,
this launch of another class

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:04.520
following up on the
Power Searching.

00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:07.540
There's a course on Mapping with
Google that teaches you

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:10.750
how to use Google Maps
and Google Earth.

00:07:10.750 --> 00:07:13.210
And here's just a little bit
more of what it looks like.

00:07:13.210 --> 00:07:16.400
So if you've seen any of these
online classes, it's sort of

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:18.040
representative of those.

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:19.590
But you can have videos.

00:07:19.590 --> 00:07:23.310
You can have exercises that
are multiple choice and

00:07:23.310 --> 00:07:26.110
fill-in-the-blank or other
types of exercises.

00:07:26.110 --> 00:07:29.320
And so this is what the
student sees, what the

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:32.720
instructor sees when they're
making the class.

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:35.760
The first version was sort of
do-it-yourself and you had to

00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:37.220
be a webmaster.

00:07:37.220 --> 00:07:39.250
Now, with this forth
version, we've got

00:07:39.250 --> 00:07:41.490
this Wiziwig interface.

00:07:41.490 --> 00:07:44.500
And so there's a rich
text editor.

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:47.240
And you type what you want, and
then you can sort of drag

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:48.420
in the various components.

00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:52.780
And here, we're dragging in a
YouTube video and a Google Doc

00:07:52.780 --> 00:07:58.580
inline and an exercise with
assessments in multiple

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:00.860
choice, or whatever.

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:06.350
And each of these components,
we've wrapped a dozen or so

00:08:06.350 --> 00:08:07.530
different types.

00:08:07.530 --> 00:08:11.320
And then, we also have an API
that describes how to wrap

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:13.170
other ones, so that you can
have your own custom

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:17.020
components that you
can then drag in.

00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:20.720
In one day, one of our engineers
put together Khan

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:23.770
Academy exercises as a
specialized component.

00:08:23.770 --> 00:08:25.720
So we just showed how
to wrap that.

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:27.650
And now, if you want--

00:08:27.650 --> 00:08:29.240
these Khan Academies
are all under

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:30.750
Creative Commons license.

00:08:30.750 --> 00:08:32.870
And so if you want to create a
class, you can just choose the

00:08:32.870 --> 00:08:34.900
one you want and drop
it into your class.

00:08:37.510 --> 00:08:40.960
So that's where we were with
the first version of Power

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:43.140
Searching and with the
tool that's now

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:45.410
available to everyone.

00:08:45.410 --> 00:08:47.310
And so you can use it as is.

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:49.120
And we wanted to do that.

00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:50.860
We also wanted to start
experimenting.

00:08:50.860 --> 00:08:53.530
To say, do we really understand
yet what's the

00:08:53.530 --> 00:08:55.800
right way to make
these classes?

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:59.300
And so we did a second version
of Power Searching.

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:02.060
And there were a couple
of experiments I

00:09:02.060 --> 00:09:03.370
wanted to do there.

00:09:03.370 --> 00:09:08.070
So first, I wanted it to be more
project-based rather than

00:09:08.070 --> 00:09:09.310
lecture-based.

00:09:09.310 --> 00:09:11.800
To say, we really want to have
the student's experience doing

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:15.830
stuff, so don't make them watch
a lecture, and then

00:09:15.830 --> 00:09:17.080
answer multiple choice.

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:18.270
Just get them right
into it and say,

00:09:18.270 --> 00:09:22.090
OK, solve this problem.

00:09:22.090 --> 00:09:23.250
There's no lectures upfront.

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:25.550
It's just a bunch of challenges
and you choose the

00:09:25.550 --> 00:09:26.590
challenges you want to do.

00:09:26.590 --> 00:09:31.450
So challenge number one says
during the glory days of

00:09:31.450 --> 00:09:34.650
radio, it was illegal to mimic
the voice of the US president.

00:09:34.650 --> 00:09:37.030
Was there actually a law
prohibiting that or was that

00:09:37.030 --> 00:09:38.420
just White House policy?

00:09:38.420 --> 00:09:40.810
And then, you're on your own.

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:44.340
You can go and try to answer
that using Google.

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:46.520
Or if you want, you can
take advantage of

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:47.570
some of these hints.

00:09:47.570 --> 00:09:51.120
So we say, here are some things
you could look at.

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:54.280
You might want to look at Google
Scholar or Google News

00:09:54.280 --> 00:09:57.930
Archive, and so on and so on.

00:09:57.930 --> 00:09:59.700
And for each of these--

00:09:59.700 --> 00:10:03.120
Here was the second experiment
I wanted to do, was saying I

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:05.770
think the first round of these
online classes went a little

00:10:05.770 --> 00:10:09.230
bit too far overboard
in using video.

00:10:09.230 --> 00:10:13.450
And we heard from 1791 some of
the disadvantages of video

00:10:13.450 --> 00:10:14.610
versus text.

00:10:14.610 --> 00:10:17.630
So I wanted to offer the video
and the text on an equal

00:10:17.630 --> 00:10:20.110
footing and have the students
decide, which one do they want

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:21.120
to consume?

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:23.580
And it turned out, it was
about 50-50, their

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:25.070
choices of which one.

00:10:25.070 --> 00:10:27.710
So if you want text,
you get it as text.

00:10:27.710 --> 00:10:30.870
If you want video, you
get it as video.

00:10:30.870 --> 00:10:34.480
And you sort of watch all
the supplemental pieces.

00:10:34.480 --> 00:10:36.990
You can also say, well,
I'm not quite ready

00:10:36.990 --> 00:10:38.040
to answer this yet.

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:39.830
Can you show me an example
of somebody

00:10:39.830 --> 00:10:41.660
solving a similar problem?

00:10:41.660 --> 00:10:43.210
And so you ask for an example.

00:10:43.210 --> 00:10:45.980
And here, we walk through the
steps of, oh, if we had this

00:10:45.980 --> 00:10:48.400
as a problem, these are the
steps we go through to

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:50.970
try to solve it.

00:10:50.970 --> 00:10:54.210
And then when you're done, you
can type in your answer.

00:10:54.210 --> 00:10:57.150
And here they've typed in, I
think it was only a policy.

00:10:57.150 --> 00:11:01.290
And type show answer.

00:11:01.290 --> 00:11:02.660
And then, see the answer.

00:11:02.660 --> 00:11:03.670
And in fact, that's right.

00:11:03.670 --> 00:11:04.640
It was a policy.

00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:07.370
And for a while we were
thinking, well, these aren't

00:11:07.370 --> 00:11:08.470
multiple choice questions.

00:11:08.470 --> 00:11:10.780
These are almost like
essay questions.

00:11:10.780 --> 00:11:14.360
And so do we need some
complicated AI software to

00:11:14.360 --> 00:11:16.790
judge whether you got
it right or not.

00:11:16.790 --> 00:11:20.360
And in the end we said, no,
we'll just let you judge.

00:11:20.360 --> 00:11:23.570
Because we're not giving
you a grade or credit.

00:11:23.570 --> 00:11:26.460
So you type in your answer, then
you see our answer and

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:28.370
you say, yeah, I got it
right, or you say,

00:11:28.370 --> 00:11:29.650
no, I got it wrong.

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:31.490
But that's up to you to judge.

00:11:31.490 --> 00:11:34.770
And students never even sort
of noticed that we weren't

00:11:34.770 --> 00:11:37.390
giving them a green check
mark or a red X mark.

00:11:37.390 --> 00:11:38.930
They just figured it
out for themselves.

00:11:41.990 --> 00:11:45.540
And then, another thing we had
was making it more social to

00:11:45.540 --> 00:11:47.720
say see how other solved
the challenge.

00:11:47.720 --> 00:11:49.040
So you can click through
on that.

00:11:49.040 --> 00:11:51.320
There's a discussion forum where
people talk about the

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:52.780
techniques they used.

00:11:52.780 --> 00:11:54.660
I like this guy here.

00:11:54.660 --> 00:11:55.720
How did you solve it?

00:11:55.720 --> 00:11:56.900
He says, I'm a law student.

00:11:56.900 --> 00:11:59.380
I just know.

00:11:59.380 --> 00:12:02.150
So not everybody needs Google
for everything.

00:12:02.150 --> 00:12:06.550
Now, I should say that when I
got into this, both in writing

00:12:06.550 --> 00:12:09.290
the textbook, teaching the
class, thinking about online

00:12:09.290 --> 00:12:14.690
education, I thought that my job
was access to information.

00:12:14.690 --> 00:12:17.100
If I put down the perfect
information and explained it

00:12:17.100 --> 00:12:19.000
in the right way, then
I've done my job.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.490
I also thought that was
true in my job as

00:12:21.490 --> 00:12:22.830
an engineer at Google.

00:12:22.830 --> 00:12:25.410
So when I was running the Search
Quality team, I thought

00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:28.730
my job is when somebody types
a hard query like that--

00:12:28.730 --> 00:12:31.300
the movie in which no
babies are born--

00:12:31.300 --> 00:12:34.610
then in 0.21 seconds, we should
give you the answer is

00:12:34.610 --> 00:12:37.390
"Children of Men." And if we
can do that and the other

00:12:37.390 --> 00:12:41.290
search engines can't, then
I've done my job.

00:12:41.290 --> 00:12:44.870
But then I realized that that
isn't everything, is just

00:12:44.870 --> 00:12:46.040
being able to get the answer.

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:50.290
And I ran across a quote from
Pablo Picasso who said that

00:12:50.290 --> 00:12:53.260
computers didn't interest him
because all they can do is

00:12:53.260 --> 00:12:54.730
give you answers.

00:12:54.730 --> 00:12:55.910
And I think he had
something there.

00:12:55.910 --> 00:12:59.100
That really, the hard part is
not coming up with the answer.

00:12:59.100 --> 00:13:03.140
I mean, I'm proud of the work
that the Google engineers are

00:13:03.140 --> 00:13:05.130
able to do to answer so well.

00:13:05.130 --> 00:13:07.390
But the really interesting part,
the part that's really

00:13:07.390 --> 00:13:09.970
educational, is that somebody
was interested

00:13:09.970 --> 00:13:12.040
enough to ask a question.

00:13:12.040 --> 00:13:15.100
And from there, the
answer is easy.

00:13:15.100 --> 00:13:18.880
I saw that when we met with
Teach for America.

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:22.530
And we had a teacher who was
given a fourth grade class in

00:13:22.530 --> 00:13:25.590
math, two years behind
grade level.

00:13:25.590 --> 00:13:27.020
And by the end of the year, had

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:28.260
everybody up to grade level.

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:30.770
So that was three years worth
of math in one year.

00:13:30.770 --> 00:13:32.230
And I said, well,
wait a minute.

00:13:32.230 --> 00:13:34.410
It wasn't information
that did that.

00:13:34.410 --> 00:13:36.800
They had the same textbook this
year that they had the

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:40.220
last year, and that other
teachers had and were

00:13:40.220 --> 00:13:41.870
unsuccessful with.

00:13:41.870 --> 00:13:43.520
So it wasn't information.

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:45.620
It was more motivation
or determination.

00:13:45.620 --> 00:13:48.400
It was this pact that the
teacher made with the student

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:50.500
saying, look, I'm going to
work really hard for you.

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:52.450
I expect you to work
hard for me.

00:13:52.450 --> 00:13:54.450
And together, we're
going to do this.

00:13:54.450 --> 00:13:57.625
That really shifted the way I
thought about what the job of

00:13:57.625 --> 00:13:59.220
a teacher is.

00:13:59.220 --> 00:14:02.110
So it's motivation,
not information.

00:14:02.110 --> 00:14:06.960
And so the aspect you really
need is willpower to work and

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:08.390
to succeed.

00:14:08.390 --> 00:14:11.670
And I thought back to my college
days and said, well,

00:14:11.670 --> 00:14:13.440
what instilled me
to get through?

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:14.330
Was it willpower?

00:14:14.330 --> 00:14:18.510
And I said, no, it
was due dates.

00:14:18.510 --> 00:14:20.350
And so we tried that.

00:14:20.350 --> 00:14:21.470
And that seemed to help.

00:14:21.470 --> 00:14:24.660
And so we think we did much
better than the classes that

00:14:24.660 --> 00:14:27.360
are open that you can
take any time.

00:14:27.360 --> 00:14:28.870
Because if you can
take it any time,

00:14:28.870 --> 00:14:29.940
you can take it tomorrow.

00:14:29.940 --> 00:14:32.830
And if you can take it tomorrow,
sometimes you

00:14:32.830 --> 00:14:33.180
never get to it.

00:14:33.180 --> 00:14:36.830
And we'll talk more about
the nuances of that.

00:14:36.830 --> 00:14:38.890
Then the peer support becomes
more important.

00:14:38.890 --> 00:14:42.160
It's not just, can you explain
things perfectly, but can you

00:14:42.160 --> 00:14:42.960
talk to somebody?

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:45.850
And can you see, hey, here's
somebody else who's working

00:14:45.850 --> 00:14:46.820
hard on this?

00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:51.090
I think that's part of what
college is all about is that

00:14:51.090 --> 00:14:54.060
it's a social environment where
you see other people who

00:14:54.060 --> 00:14:55.390
are also studying.

00:14:55.390 --> 00:14:57.020
Well, they're partying, too.

00:14:57.020 --> 00:14:59.730
And that's part of
college as well.

00:14:59.730 --> 00:15:03.240
But seeing them dedicated to
work and saying I can be part

00:15:03.240 --> 00:15:06.070
of that community that's
working is important.

00:15:06.070 --> 00:15:08.610
The faculty encouragement
was important.

00:15:08.610 --> 00:15:10.610
So every week we sent out
an email that said,

00:15:10.610 --> 00:15:12.950
congratulations, keep going.

00:15:12.950 --> 00:15:15.840
And every week, I'd get a dozen
or so back that says,

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:20.880
oh, professor, something tough
came up in my work life.

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:22.820
And I was going to drop the
class, but then I saw your

00:15:22.820 --> 00:15:25.300
email and I realized
I had to go on.

00:15:25.300 --> 00:15:29.820
And I felt like saying that
was a form letter.

00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:33.520
You do realize I didn't write
100,000 personal letters to

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:35.140
each of you?

00:15:35.140 --> 00:15:36.380
But it works.

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:40.280
So just that level of human
connection, even though it is

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:43.090
a form letter, it makes
a big difference.

00:15:43.090 --> 00:15:46.630
I think there's a pride of
accomplishment we need to

00:15:46.630 --> 00:15:47.800
accommodate.

00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:53.130
This authenticity of this
is the real thing.

00:15:53.130 --> 00:15:56.570
This is a Stanford-level class
that I'm taking and I have

00:15:56.570 --> 00:15:59.170
this opportunity to
learn this stuff.

00:15:59.170 --> 00:16:01.570
I think the excitement of being
in the early stages of

00:16:01.570 --> 00:16:04.440
something new has all
contributed to why people

00:16:04.440 --> 00:16:06.920
wanted to do this.

00:16:06.920 --> 00:16:09.900
And this is just pointing out
sort of the depth of the

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:13.190
social engagement, that people
used all sorts of--

00:16:13.190 --> 00:16:16.040
any social networking site you
can see on the web, people

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:19.730
were using that to connect
with each other.

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:20.430
And here I show--

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:23.500
I got this from Coursera, from
one of their classes.

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:26.590
This is a timeline of how
many people are online.

00:16:26.590 --> 00:16:30.440
And like all classes, you can
see the superimposition of

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:30.910
three things.

00:16:30.910 --> 00:16:34.560
So there's a ramp up at the
beginning and there's

00:16:34.560 --> 00:16:36.570
exponential decay over time.

00:16:36.570 --> 00:16:37.920
Actually, a lot of
classes have much

00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:39.940
steeper exponential decay.

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:43.880
I think this is the one that
Coursera chose to release, was

00:16:43.880 --> 00:16:46.070
the one that has a
shallow decay.

00:16:46.070 --> 00:16:47.590
And then, you can see
the due dates

00:16:47.590 --> 00:16:51.620
interspersed, those big spikes.

00:16:51.620 --> 00:16:53.770
And I think there's still this
controversy that I haven't

00:16:53.770 --> 00:16:56.670
quite figured out yet of how
important are those due dates?

00:16:56.670 --> 00:16:59.320
So certainly, they do make
people come back.

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:01.500
They do make them work hard.

00:17:01.500 --> 00:17:04.040
But on the other hand, they
also make people drop out.

00:17:04.040 --> 00:17:07.119
If you miss the due date, then
you say, oh, well, now 'm not

00:17:07.119 --> 00:17:08.902
going to get a perfect
score and I might as

00:17:08.902 --> 00:17:10.950
well just give up.

00:17:10.950 --> 00:17:14.980
So I think we need to think
more about what

00:17:14.980 --> 00:17:15.829
the processes are.

00:17:15.829 --> 00:17:18.460
So I've talked about these.

00:17:18.460 --> 00:17:21.460
You can have a synchronous
class, that's the in-class,

00:17:21.460 --> 00:17:23.210
Stanford class, that
meets at 9:00 AM.

00:17:23.210 --> 00:17:25.369
And if you're late,
you missed it.

00:17:25.369 --> 00:17:27.280
You can have these
evergreen classes

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:29.320
that are always available.

00:17:29.320 --> 00:17:32.190
The MIT OpenCourseWare, it's
anytime you want to do

00:17:32.190 --> 00:17:33.670
it you can do it.

00:17:33.670 --> 00:17:36.180
But then you miss the motivation
of the due dates.

00:17:36.180 --> 00:17:38.560
Our class we called
semi-synchronous, which meant

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:41.020
there was a due date every week,
but during the week you

00:17:41.020 --> 00:17:42.090
could interact with the

00:17:42.090 --> 00:17:44.300
materials at your own schedule.

00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:47.330
I'd like to get to a model I
call the bus route model,

00:17:47.330 --> 00:17:49.870
which says that there's a
schedule and you get on, you

00:17:49.870 --> 00:17:51.920
start doing the class.

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:54.670
But if something comes up at
work or at home and you get

00:17:54.670 --> 00:17:57.540
stuck, you can get off the bus
and say, OK, I'm taking a

00:17:57.540 --> 00:17:59.020
timeout now.

00:17:59.020 --> 00:18:00.560
It's going to be fast for me.

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:01.690
I have to stop.

00:18:01.690 --> 00:18:04.060
But then you know at some point
in the future, there's

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:04.600
another bus.

00:18:04.600 --> 00:18:08.140
You can get back on and
finish the class.

00:18:08.140 --> 00:18:10.300
OK, now the big question.

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:12.120
What's learning?

00:18:12.120 --> 00:18:15.610
One of my heroes, and one of the
founders of the field of

00:18:15.610 --> 00:18:16.640
AI, is Herb Simon.

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:19.710
And he reminds us that learning
is something that the

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:20.530
student does.

00:18:20.530 --> 00:18:22.700
And I think as teachers,
sometimes we forget that.

00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:25.070
We think it's something that
we, as teachers, do.

00:18:25.070 --> 00:18:27.310
And that's not right.

00:18:27.310 --> 00:18:29.700
Learning only happens in
the student's head.

00:18:29.700 --> 00:18:32.682
And our job is just there
to facilitate it.

00:18:32.682 --> 00:18:36.820
And so I think what that means
is it's not how well can I

00:18:36.820 --> 00:18:37.790
explain it.

00:18:37.790 --> 00:18:40.530
It's how much can
the student do?

00:18:40.530 --> 00:18:43.590
And so we tried to make our
class so that the students

00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:45.230
were doing the problems first.

00:18:45.230 --> 00:18:46.490
And then they would get
the explanation.

00:18:49.240 --> 00:18:51.360
We forced students to
make predictions.

00:18:51.360 --> 00:18:52.860
To say, here's a
new situation.

00:18:52.860 --> 00:18:54.105
What do you think is
going to happen?

00:18:54.105 --> 00:18:57.580
And the reason we did that is
because we knew, from the

00:18:57.580 --> 00:19:00.940
scientific literature, that if
students have a misconception

00:19:00.940 --> 00:19:03.720
of some kind and you give them
an explanation, no matter how

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:06.900
great that explanation is, it's
not going to dissuade

00:19:06.900 --> 00:19:08.210
them from their misconception.

00:19:08.210 --> 00:19:09.410
They're going to say, yeah.

00:19:09.410 --> 00:19:10.480
I got it.

00:19:10.480 --> 00:19:12.290
Then you give them a problem
and they still do it their

00:19:12.290 --> 00:19:13.540
old, wrong way.

00:19:13.540 --> 00:19:15.570
And the only way you get them
out of that is to say, OK, do

00:19:15.570 --> 00:19:17.150
it your way.

00:19:17.150 --> 00:19:18.360
Here's a contradiction.

00:19:18.360 --> 00:19:20.240
Your way did something wrong.

00:19:20.240 --> 00:19:21.750
And then they're ready
to think about it.

00:19:21.750 --> 00:19:24.950
So we made them make
those predictions.

00:19:24.950 --> 00:19:27.910
And I got to say, students
didn't like that in general.

00:19:27.910 --> 00:19:29.900
That they said, well, no fair.

00:19:29.900 --> 00:19:32.340
You didn't give us
the formula.

00:19:32.340 --> 00:19:34.510
I can fill in the blanks in
the formula if you tell me

00:19:34.510 --> 00:19:36.810
every step of how to do it.

00:19:36.810 --> 00:19:40.880
But it's no fair to make me
think and do it ahead of time.

00:19:40.880 --> 00:19:43.350
And I should say, we were also a
little bit clumsy in the way

00:19:43.350 --> 00:19:48.710
we specified things, in that we
gave them these problems.

00:19:48.710 --> 00:19:49.850
We said, well, don't worry.

00:19:49.850 --> 00:19:51.240
It doesn't matter if you
get it right or wrong.

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:52.960
We just want you to
think about it.

00:19:52.960 --> 00:19:55.660
But then in the end, we gave
them a check mark when they

00:19:55.660 --> 00:19:56.300
got it right.

00:19:56.300 --> 00:19:59.930
And so people had been drummed
in so much to say, well, the

00:19:59.930 --> 00:20:02.970
important thing is whether you
get it right or wrong.

00:20:02.970 --> 00:20:06.240
And that's how school works.

00:20:06.240 --> 00:20:08.930
We need to figure out ways to do
a better job to say that's

00:20:08.930 --> 00:20:09.900
not the important thing.

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:13.700
Playing with the material
is the important thing.

00:20:13.700 --> 00:20:16.440
We like to have experiments with
more open-ended problems.

00:20:16.440 --> 00:20:18.810
It's easiest to do a
fill-in-the-blank or multiple

00:20:18.810 --> 00:20:21.090
choice because we know
how to grade those.

00:20:21.090 --> 00:20:22.750
But those aren't the
most fulfilling.

00:20:22.750 --> 00:20:25.000
And there have been some
experiments with peer grading

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:28.920
where you write an essay or
design a project of some kind,

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:31.250
and then have several of your
peers grade it and average

00:20:31.250 --> 00:20:31.950
those grades.

00:20:31.950 --> 00:20:35.440
It turns out that works
pretty well.

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:39.290
Now, I talked with Hal Varian,
who's Google Chief Economist.

00:20:39.290 --> 00:20:42.820
And when he was at Bell Labs,
he wrote the textbook on

00:20:42.820 --> 00:20:43.280
microeconomics.

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:45.770
It's one of the standards
in the field.

00:20:45.770 --> 00:20:48.790
And he was there with Richard
Hamming, who you may know from

00:20:48.790 --> 00:20:53.567
Hamming Codes and so on, and Hal
said that Hamming told him

00:20:53.567 --> 00:20:54.340
his secret.

00:20:54.340 --> 00:20:56.100
That the way you write a
textbook is first yo get

00:20:56.100 --> 00:20:58.400
together the problem sets and
the exams that you want the

00:20:58.400 --> 00:20:59.960
students to be able to solve.

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:01.200
And then you write a book
that teaches them

00:21:01.200 --> 00:21:02.360
how to solve them.

00:21:02.360 --> 00:21:04.040
So I think this fits in
well with this idea

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:06.160
of learning is doing.

00:21:06.160 --> 00:21:08.940
And when Hal was explaining
this to me I

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:11.210
said, hey, I know that.

00:21:11.210 --> 00:21:14.090
In software development, we
call that test-driven

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:15.980
development.

00:21:15.980 --> 00:21:19.590
So you write a bunch of m
then the tests fails.

00:21:19.590 --> 00:21:21.300
And then you have to
write some code.

00:21:21.300 --> 00:21:22.910
And so it's the same
with a textbook.

00:21:22.910 --> 00:21:26.020
You should start with a blank
textbook, write the problems

00:21:26.020 --> 00:21:27.670
in the back, hit go.

00:21:27.670 --> 00:21:30.790
And every time there's a red
mark where the test doesn't

00:21:30.790 --> 00:21:33.160
succeed, then you have to write
a chapter or a section

00:21:33.160 --> 00:21:34.430
of the textbook.

00:21:34.430 --> 00:21:36.090
So I think that makes sense.

00:21:36.090 --> 00:21:38.180
I think the one thing you have
to be careful about then, do

00:21:38.180 --> 00:21:40.320
you end up sort of teaching
to the test?

00:21:40.320 --> 00:21:43.790
So it only works if the test
problems that you've chosen

00:21:43.790 --> 00:21:47.370
are the skills that you really
want people to have, not if

00:21:47.370 --> 00:21:51.050
they're just sort of
arbitrary things.

00:21:51.050 --> 00:21:52.270
So remember Bloom.

00:21:52.270 --> 00:21:55.160
He was the guy who wrote
the one paper that

00:21:55.160 --> 00:21:56.660
you had to know about.

00:21:56.660 --> 00:21:58.480
How much do we trust him?

00:21:58.480 --> 00:22:02.180
Is he right that one-on-one
learning is the

00:22:02.180 --> 00:22:03.910
most important thing?

00:22:03.910 --> 00:22:06.630
Well, Kurt VanLehn, from
Arizona State, did a

00:22:06.630 --> 00:22:09.130
meta-analysis of
this recently.

00:22:09.130 --> 00:22:13.590
I think this was from
2011 or 2012.

00:22:13.590 --> 00:22:16.830
And Kurt says, here's the
conventional wisdom.

00:22:16.830 --> 00:22:18.460
The conventional wisdom says--

00:22:18.460 --> 00:22:21.550
Bloom claimed that if you had
this human tutor, you'd get

00:22:21.550 --> 00:22:24.150
two standard deviations
of improvement.

00:22:24.150 --> 00:22:28.440
If you have a intelligent
tutoring system, the sort of

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:31.110
state-of-the-art computer
system, you get one.

00:22:31.110 --> 00:22:33.700
And if you just have the paper
and pencil fill-in-the-blank

00:22:33.700 --> 00:22:37.550
type thing, you get
a quarter or so.

00:22:37.550 --> 00:22:41.160
And that's sort of what's in the
literature, or the sort of

00:22:41.160 --> 00:22:42.600
expectations that people have.

00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:45.210
But he looked very carefully at
every study he could find

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:47.290
and averaged them all out
and found out it's

00:22:47.290 --> 00:22:49.550
not quite like that.

00:22:49.550 --> 00:22:52.400
That you don't always get these
two standard deviations

00:22:52.400 --> 00:22:53.280
of improvement.

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:57.180
And in fact, the good
computerized systems are doing

00:22:57.180 --> 00:23:00.190
just as well as a human tutor.

00:23:00.190 --> 00:23:03.540
And the other thing he found is
that it wasn't so much the

00:23:03.540 --> 00:23:05.070
one-on-one tutoring.

00:23:05.070 --> 00:23:07.170
The more important part was
the mastery learning.

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:10.590
So mastery learning, again,
means you keep on learning

00:23:10.590 --> 00:23:14.480
until you've got it, which seems
the obvious thing to do.

00:23:14.480 --> 00:23:17.060
But mostly, we don't do that
because we've got a whole

00:23:17.060 --> 00:23:20.120
class of 30 or 50 or 200
students, or whatever, and we

00:23:20.120 --> 00:23:21.950
got to move ahead at
a certain pace.

00:23:21.950 --> 00:23:23.590
So we say, well, we're going
to learn this for

00:23:23.590 --> 00:23:24.400
this amount of time.

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:25.070
Then, there's going
to be a test.

00:23:25.070 --> 00:23:27.010
Then we're going to do
the next subject.

00:23:27.010 --> 00:23:28.480
Salman Khan talks about that.

00:23:28.480 --> 00:23:30.240
He says, this is crazy.

00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:33.350
So this is like if I was
teaching you to ride a bicycle

00:23:33.350 --> 00:23:35.700
and you ride for a while and
you keep on falling down.

00:23:35.700 --> 00:23:36.670
Then you'd say, OK, great.

00:23:36.670 --> 00:23:39.080
Now we're going to learn
unicycle because it's time for

00:23:39.080 --> 00:23:40.330
the next unit.

00:23:40.330 --> 00:23:42.640
That wouldn't make sense and you
wouldn't learn to ride a

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:44.180
bicycle that way.

00:23:44.180 --> 00:23:47.330
But if we kept at it until you
stopped falling down, and then

00:23:47.330 --> 00:23:50.500
with a sufficiently large
box of Band-Aids,

00:23:50.500 --> 00:23:52.700
everyone would get it.

00:23:52.700 --> 00:23:55.460
And that's what we need to do
for education is let people

00:23:55.460 --> 00:23:58.090
take their own time, until
everyone gets it, and then you

00:23:58.090 --> 00:23:59.440
can move on to the unicycle.

00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:04.740
So I think those are the
interesting lessons from that.

00:24:04.740 --> 00:24:06.400
And then there's one more lesson
that I thought was

00:24:06.400 --> 00:24:09.212
fascinating, is that--

00:24:09.212 --> 00:24:11.290
there were a couple
dozen studies.

00:24:11.290 --> 00:24:13.660
Out of all we spend in
education, there was only a

00:24:13.660 --> 00:24:16.350
couple dozen studies that went
into this meta-study.

00:24:16.350 --> 00:24:19.770
And sort of the canonical one,
the one that people cite the

00:24:19.770 --> 00:24:23.460
most has 33 students in it.

00:24:23.460 --> 00:24:27.790
So it's like, we're deciding
the future of our education

00:24:27.790 --> 00:24:29.500
based on 33 people.

00:24:29.500 --> 00:24:32.100
And maybe 10 of them had a bad
day and we got the wrong

00:24:32.100 --> 00:24:33.520
conclusion.

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:35.760
But now, we have the capability,
when we bring this

00:24:35.760 --> 00:24:39.960
stuff online, we can base
things on 33,000 or 33

00:24:39.960 --> 00:24:44.090
million, rather than just
a small sampling.

00:24:44.090 --> 00:24:45.830
We're able to collect more
data and get more

00:24:45.830 --> 00:24:46.620
feedback from it.

00:24:46.620 --> 00:24:48.110
So I think that's exciting.

00:24:48.110 --> 00:24:53.010
So the question then is, how
do we get the advantages?

00:24:53.010 --> 00:24:55.820
We can argue about exactly how
much, but we know one-on-one

00:24:55.820 --> 00:24:58.280
tutoring and mastery learning
are important.

00:24:58.280 --> 00:25:01.250
Can we get them without having
to hire a private tutor for

00:25:01.250 --> 00:25:03.650
every student?

00:25:03.650 --> 00:25:05.440
Is technology the answer?

00:25:05.440 --> 00:25:08.950
Well, technology has always
been the answer.

00:25:08.950 --> 00:25:13.270
So all these technologies listed
here, movies and radio

00:25:13.270 --> 00:25:14.810
and TVs and so on, we're
going to solve

00:25:14.810 --> 00:25:17.230
the education problem.

00:25:17.230 --> 00:25:20.440
And one of the earliest
examples, besides the 1791

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:24.290
example, is this is Thomas
Edison featured here with

00:25:24.290 --> 00:25:26.670
Eastman from Eastman Kodak.

00:25:26.670 --> 00:25:31.220
And in 1913, Edison said that
books will soon be obsolete in

00:25:31.220 --> 00:25:32.900
the public schools.

00:25:32.900 --> 00:25:34.780
Scholars will be instructed
through the eye.

00:25:34.780 --> 00:25:37.330
It's possible to teach every
branch of human knowledge with

00:25:37.330 --> 00:25:38.760
the motion picture.

00:25:38.760 --> 00:25:40.710
Our school system will
be completely changed

00:25:40.710 --> 00:25:42.650
inside of 10 years.

00:25:42.650 --> 00:25:45.040
And you could take that last
sentence about the 10 years

00:25:45.040 --> 00:25:48.460
and apply it to every technology
since then.

00:25:48.460 --> 00:25:51.310
And the question is, are we now
at a point where anything

00:25:51.310 --> 00:25:52.120
is any different?

00:25:52.120 --> 00:25:55.220
Or 10 years from now, are we
going to say, well, that

00:25:55.220 --> 00:25:55.760
didn't work.

00:25:55.760 --> 00:25:57.940
And now there's a new technology
and that'll work 10

00:25:57.940 --> 00:26:00.960
years from now.

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:02.435
So what's different?

00:26:02.435 --> 00:26:06.445
Well, if you look at these four
characters and say, what

00:26:06.445 --> 00:26:08.850
do they have in common?

00:26:08.850 --> 00:26:11.590
There's probably two answers
that you come up with that

00:26:11.590 --> 00:26:13.670
we've all been involved in
these online classes.

00:26:13.670 --> 00:26:16.220
And we're all involved in
artificial intelligence.

00:26:16.220 --> 00:26:18.780
And I think there's something
about that.

00:26:18.780 --> 00:26:21.910
That this idea that you can
learn from large amounts of

00:26:21.910 --> 00:26:24.960
data, naturally sort of
attracted all of us to say

00:26:24.960 --> 00:26:27.290
this is an application where
we can take that

00:26:27.290 --> 00:26:28.740
data and apply it.

00:26:28.740 --> 00:26:31.840
And maybe make rapid improvement
in education the

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:34.950
way we have in other fields,
like computer vision, in

00:26:34.950 --> 00:26:36.520
speech recognition, so on.

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:39.270
We've seen that now is the
time when it's right.

00:26:39.270 --> 00:26:42.300
We've gone from having speech
recognition that's pretty

00:26:42.300 --> 00:26:45.430
crappy to speech recognition
that's now pretty good.

00:26:45.430 --> 00:26:47.430
And it didn't really
take a single

00:26:47.430 --> 00:26:49.760
breakthrough or a new theory.

00:26:49.760 --> 00:26:52.080
Most of it was driven just
by having better data.

00:26:54.740 --> 00:26:58.200
Now, here's the traditional
model of data.

00:26:58.200 --> 00:27:01.570
What you get from your four
years in college is a

00:27:01.570 --> 00:27:03.650
transcript that looks
like this.

00:27:03.650 --> 00:27:10.760
And that works out to about 20
bits of information per year.

00:27:10.760 --> 00:27:14.600
Now, here's a consumer
electronics device.

00:27:14.600 --> 00:27:18.700
And that's about 192,000
bits per second.

00:27:18.700 --> 00:27:20.690
So that's about a trillion
times more.

00:27:20.690 --> 00:27:23.670
You also notice that the one
on the left costs more than

00:27:23.670 --> 00:27:25.840
the one on the right.

00:27:25.840 --> 00:27:28.200
So the bitrate per
dollar is about a

00:27:28.200 --> 00:27:29.830
quadrillion times better.

00:27:29.830 --> 00:27:31.510
So it seems like we should be
able to do better than the

00:27:31.510 --> 00:27:32.520
transcript.

00:27:32.520 --> 00:27:35.240
So we should be able to gather
more information, have a

00:27:35.240 --> 00:27:38.490
better picture of you as an
individual, both to represent

00:27:38.490 --> 00:27:42.540
you to a prospective employer
and so on, and also to

00:27:42.540 --> 00:27:46.020
aggregate that information
across all the students so

00:27:46.020 --> 00:27:48.990
that we can make a rapid
improvement in

00:27:48.990 --> 00:27:50.890
the pedagogy itself.

00:27:50.890 --> 00:27:54.260
Now, if you've seen other talks
I've given, this is a

00:27:54.260 --> 00:27:57.960
chart I show where I say in
lots of application that

00:27:57.960 --> 00:27:59.970
Google comes up with--

00:27:59.970 --> 00:28:02.080
in search, in speech
recognition, in image

00:28:02.080 --> 00:28:03.530
recognition and so on--

00:28:03.530 --> 00:28:07.240
we often have a response curve
that looks like this.

00:28:07.240 --> 00:28:10.430
Where we say we apply some
algorithm to a problem and you

00:28:10.430 --> 00:28:13.040
give it a little bit of data,
and the algorithm's performing

00:28:13.040 --> 00:28:14.040
pretty badly.

00:28:14.040 --> 00:28:16.290
But instead of giving up and
going home, you went out and

00:28:16.290 --> 00:28:17.460
gathered more data.

00:28:17.460 --> 00:28:18.720
And all of a sudden,
the algorithm

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:19.980
starts to get better.

00:28:19.980 --> 00:28:22.650
And the hope is that education
is going to turn

00:28:22.650 --> 00:28:23.480
out to be like this.

00:28:23.480 --> 00:28:25.160
And we haven't cashed
in on that hope yet.

00:28:25.160 --> 00:28:26.210
We're just getting started.

00:28:26.210 --> 00:28:28.980
Nobody knows if it's going
to work or not.

00:28:28.980 --> 00:28:33.740
But I think this is what
we're all fighting for.

00:28:33.740 --> 00:28:36.150
Now, last thing I want to
talk about is how you

00:28:36.150 --> 00:28:37.870
put together a class.

00:28:37.870 --> 00:28:41.780
And this also is
from Coursera.

00:28:41.780 --> 00:28:43.410
I asked them, what's your most

00:28:43.410 --> 00:28:45.210
complicated branching structure?

00:28:45.210 --> 00:28:47.280
And they said, well, we got a
genomics class that's got

00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:48.890
these main components.

00:28:48.890 --> 00:28:51.820
And then there's a sort of
introductory class that feeds

00:28:51.820 --> 00:28:56.030
into that and an advanced class
that follows up on that.

00:28:56.030 --> 00:29:00.940
So on the order of a dozen or
two units that are linked

00:29:00.940 --> 00:29:04.410
together in this complex
graphing structure.

00:29:04.410 --> 00:29:06.160
Now, compare that
to this graph.

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:07.940
Can you all see that
in the back?

00:29:07.940 --> 00:29:09.120
That all clear?

00:29:09.120 --> 00:29:12.180
You can read those labels?

00:29:12.180 --> 00:29:14.410
So this is from Wikipedia
and this is all

00:29:14.410 --> 00:29:15.485
the mammals in Wikipedia.

00:29:15.485 --> 00:29:19.270
So about 7,000 entries
and a dense link

00:29:19.270 --> 00:29:20.900
structure between them.

00:29:20.900 --> 00:29:23.990
So very different than
the other graph.

00:29:23.990 --> 00:29:26.370
But in some sense, that's
not ideal either.

00:29:26.370 --> 00:29:28.125
I don't want it just-- if you
want to learn about mammals, I

00:29:28.125 --> 00:29:29.680
don't want to just
give you that.

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:32.170
I want to give you some
guidance through it.

00:29:32.170 --> 00:29:34.430
And so what I would like to do
is be able to combine these

00:29:34.430 --> 00:29:39.700
two models to say what we really
need is some guide from

00:29:39.700 --> 00:29:42.360
a teacher, or some pathways
through this material.

00:29:42.360 --> 00:29:45.560
And here I've shown three
different pathways, three

00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:49.640
guides that says here's one way
to look at this material.

00:29:49.640 --> 00:29:51.570
And it's a branching
structure.

00:29:51.570 --> 00:29:54.600
And now you have a choice
as a student.

00:29:54.600 --> 00:29:56.580
I could choose the guide I like
and I could stick with

00:29:56.580 --> 00:29:58.870
them and follow them
along the path.

00:29:58.870 --> 00:30:01.930
Or, maybe I can switch to
another guide if I find I

00:30:01.930 --> 00:30:03.510
don't like that one or
if I want more than

00:30:03.510 --> 00:30:04.830
one point of view.

00:30:04.830 --> 00:30:06.800
And if I want, I can
go off-road.

00:30:06.800 --> 00:30:09.190
I can say, well, the guide's
taken me this far, but here's

00:30:09.190 --> 00:30:11.550
some interesting stuff
that's off the path.

00:30:11.550 --> 00:30:13.540
And I'm going to take a
diversion and follow off the

00:30:13.540 --> 00:30:16.030
path and on into Wikipedia.

00:30:16.030 --> 00:30:18.910
So I think we want to build
a system that allows that.

00:30:18.910 --> 00:30:22.340
Now, the problem is, who's
going to build it?

00:30:22.340 --> 00:30:25.070
I want to make an analogy of
something I call courseware

00:30:25.070 --> 00:30:27.740
engineering to software
engineering.

00:30:27.740 --> 00:30:31.360
Now, in the early days of
software, systems were built

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:32.910
by small teams.

00:30:32.910 --> 00:30:34.450
Here we have one guy.

00:30:34.450 --> 00:30:38.070
This is Bernstein working
on his chess program.

00:30:38.070 --> 00:30:40.840
Here's Wozniak working on
his operating system.

00:30:40.840 --> 00:30:43.850
And in those days, one guy or
a small team could build an

00:30:43.850 --> 00:30:44.660
operating system.

00:30:44.660 --> 00:30:45.940
But those days are gone.

00:30:45.940 --> 00:30:48.940
Now we want to build more
complex objects.

00:30:48.940 --> 00:30:51.550
And we worked out a system of
software engineering so that a

00:30:51.550 --> 00:30:54.470
team like this-- these guys
built a video game.

00:30:54.470 --> 00:30:58.030
We know how we can get teams
of dozens or hundreds of

00:30:58.030 --> 00:31:00.260
people to build something
bigger than one or

00:31:00.260 --> 00:31:01.740
two people can build.

00:31:01.740 --> 00:31:03.880
But in education, we're
not doing that yet.

00:31:03.880 --> 00:31:06.620
Courses are still built by one
or two people at a time.

00:31:06.620 --> 00:31:10.180
We want to find a way to be
able to put that together.

00:31:10.180 --> 00:31:12.420
So what's this doing here?

00:31:12.420 --> 00:31:17.130
Well, in some domains, the
artisanal product is what you

00:31:17.130 --> 00:31:18.290
really want.

00:31:18.290 --> 00:31:22.800
So I want a master cheese
maker to be making me my

00:31:22.800 --> 00:31:25.180
cheese by hand.

00:31:25.180 --> 00:31:28.530
And I don't want the mass
produced product.

00:31:28.530 --> 00:31:29.650
And courses are like that.

00:31:29.650 --> 00:31:32.120
And I want to maintain the best
part of the courses of

00:31:32.120 --> 00:31:34.380
saying, here's this
expert teacher.

00:31:34.380 --> 00:31:35.760
They have years of experience.

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:37.230
I don't want to lose that.

00:31:37.230 --> 00:31:40.340
On the other hand, there are
other domains where the mass

00:31:40.340 --> 00:31:43.500
produced product is
better than the

00:31:43.500 --> 00:31:45.610
individually produced one.

00:31:45.610 --> 00:31:47.630
And I want to allow us
to do that as well.

00:31:47.630 --> 00:31:51.170
To be able to say, can we
combine these experts and have

00:31:51.170 --> 00:31:54.240
them build something so that
we get the best of both?

00:31:54.240 --> 00:31:58.630
We get this large graph, but
superimposed on top of that we

00:31:58.630 --> 00:32:00.690
have the individual expertise.

00:32:00.690 --> 00:32:03.570
And that's where we're trying
to be head for, is

00:32:03.570 --> 00:32:04.960
to allow for that.

00:32:04.960 --> 00:32:08.750
Now, we built Course Builder
and it's a tool that allows

00:32:08.750 --> 00:32:12.160
you to experiment in building
your own class.

00:32:12.160 --> 00:32:14.580
I don't know how long it's
going take to get here.

00:32:14.580 --> 00:32:16.160
But that's why I'm in it.

00:32:16.160 --> 00:32:17.680
And so I guess we
got eight and a

00:32:17.680 --> 00:32:19.850
half minutes for questions.

00:32:19.850 --> 00:32:22.940
And then afterwards, this is
the last session so you can

00:32:22.940 --> 00:32:23.810
stay as long as you want.

00:32:23.810 --> 00:32:27.040
And we've got some laptops set
up here where you can play

00:32:27.040 --> 00:32:31.920
with Course Builder or you
can talk to us after.

00:32:31.920 --> 00:32:34.020
So if there's any questions,
you can make

00:32:34.020 --> 00:32:35.658
your way to the mics.

