00:37:38.060 --> 00:37:39.150
explore in.

00:37:39.150 --> 00:37:42.970
It's got to be this dense
graph-like thing where they

00:37:42.970 --> 00:37:45.490
can go in the direction
they want.

00:37:45.490 --> 00:37:48.520
And I think also that
we want to think of

00:37:48.520 --> 00:37:50.070
this as being a tool.

00:37:50.070 --> 00:37:51.820
It's not like it's
a replacement.

00:37:51.820 --> 00:37:53.660
It's not like they don't
have school.

00:37:53.660 --> 00:37:54.205
They don't have teachers.

00:37:54.205 --> 00:37:56.230
They don't have anything else,
they're just stuck

00:37:56.230 --> 00:37:57.790
in front of a screen.

00:37:57.790 --> 00:38:02.880
It's like this is one more tool
and they have books, and

00:38:02.880 --> 00:38:05.000
finger paints, and
everything else

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:06.290
they have in the classroom.

00:38:06.290 --> 00:38:08.930
And this is one more thing for
them to play with part of the

00:38:08.930 --> 00:38:10.970
time, but not the only tool.

00:38:14.090 --> 00:38:16.360
AUDIENCE: Hi there, my name
is Jarom McDonald.

00:38:16.360 --> 00:38:18.890
I'm the Director of Digital
Humanities at Brigham Young

00:38:18.890 --> 00:38:20.510
University.

00:38:20.510 --> 00:38:24.540
And myself, growing up with
technology and being in the

00:38:24.540 --> 00:38:27.460
development world as well, a
lot of what you talk about

00:38:27.460 --> 00:38:28.060
makes sense.

00:38:28.060 --> 00:38:31.530
But having academic training in
the humanities and working

00:38:31.530 --> 00:38:33.770
with humanities faculty on a
regular basis, I encounter a

00:38:33.770 --> 00:38:35.790
lot of general technophobia
anyway.

00:38:35.790 --> 00:38:39.190
And over the past year and a
half, as we've been discussing

00:38:39.190 --> 00:38:42.190
issues of the types of things
you're talking about, there's

00:38:42.190 --> 00:38:45.440
a lot of resistance we encounter
among literature

00:38:45.440 --> 00:38:48.310
professors, professors of art,
history, and so forth.

00:38:48.310 --> 00:38:51.970
And I was wondering, whether
from your personal kind of

00:38:51.970 --> 00:38:55.700
outlook and paradigm, or even
from actual experience, what

00:38:55.700 --> 00:38:59.090
sorts of things you might have
to say in terms of the ability

00:38:59.090 --> 00:39:01.500
to handle the types of problems
that humanities

00:39:01.500 --> 00:39:03.490
education is dealing with,
specifically literature, art,

00:39:03.490 --> 00:39:05.550
and history.

00:39:05.550 --> 00:39:06.000
PETER NORVIG: Yeah.

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:10.440
So there certainly have been
classes that do that, that

00:39:10.440 --> 00:39:11.450
have worked out well.

00:39:11.450 --> 00:39:15.130
I think it's required a lot
of work on the part of the

00:39:15.130 --> 00:39:18.040
creators of the class
in order to do that.

00:39:18.040 --> 00:39:23.490
So it's much easier to do a
math class because I can

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:26.300
generate an infinite number of
subtraction problems for which

00:39:26.300 --> 00:39:27.710
I know the right answer.

00:39:27.710 --> 00:39:30.470
And generate them randomly
and test students

00:39:30.470 --> 00:39:32.240
and get that right.

00:39:32.240 --> 00:39:34.080
I can't do that for an infinite

00:39:34.080 --> 00:39:35.330
number of essay questions.

00:39:38.170 --> 00:39:40.760
The social structure of the
class is different .

00:39:40.760 --> 00:39:44.050
It has to not just be you watch
something and then you

00:39:44.050 --> 00:39:46.080
fill in the blank and it's
automatically graded.

00:39:46.080 --> 00:39:49.300
Rather, it has to be you're
collaborating with other

00:39:49.300 --> 00:39:52.690
people, you're talking
with them.

00:39:52.690 --> 00:39:56.530
They're grading you're essays
and you're grading theirs.

00:39:56.530 --> 00:40:00.140
And you're having discussions.

00:40:00.140 --> 00:40:03.760
Sort of the structure of the
class is more complex.

00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:06.170
But I think it can be done and
I think there are advantages

00:40:06.170 --> 00:40:07.516
to doing that.

00:40:07.516 --> 00:40:12.300
That you can have more immediate
feedback that way.

00:40:12.300 --> 00:40:15.320
And you can maybe reach
more people.

00:40:15.320 --> 00:40:18.920
So it's this--

00:40:18.920 --> 00:40:21.330
the paragon of liberal
education, where you have a

00:40:21.330 --> 00:40:24.730
small seminar with an expert
teacher and 10

00:40:24.730 --> 00:40:26.320
students at a time.

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:28.550
That's great, but
it's expensive.

00:40:28.550 --> 00:40:32.120
And if we can get close to that,
but be able to do many

00:40:32.120 --> 00:40:34.160
more than 10 students at a time,
I think that's something

00:40:34.160 --> 00:40:35.410
worth considering.

00:40:37.560 --> 00:40:39.170
AUDIENCE: My name's Wyatt
Anderson and I work for an

00:40:39.170 --> 00:40:40.420
