00:40:56.750 --> 00:40:57.470
into our learning.

00:40:57.470 --> 00:40:59.490
And I'm wondering, what kind of

00:40:59.490 --> 00:41:03.400
challenges do you see with--

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:06.320
when you integrate a social
experience into the sort of

00:41:06.320 --> 00:41:09.910
like online coursework system
with regard to the efficacy of

00:41:09.910 --> 00:41:11.160
the course.

00:41:13.760 --> 00:41:16.200
What benefit to the
effectiveness of the education

00:41:16.200 --> 00:41:18.730
do you see that sort of
social interaction

00:41:18.730 --> 00:41:19.760
with your peers providing?

00:41:19.760 --> 00:41:22.050
Do you think that's a valid
direction for education?

00:41:22.050 --> 00:41:22.600
PETER NORVIG: Yeah.

00:41:22.600 --> 00:41:26.100
I think we still have to
understand how best to use

00:41:26.100 --> 00:41:27.350
these social interaction.

00:41:30.140 --> 00:41:34.450
So I did my class and I go on
the discussion forums and I

00:41:34.450 --> 00:41:35.160
say, oh, wow.

00:41:35.160 --> 00:41:38.630
This is so great because
students are asking questions.

00:41:38.630 --> 00:41:41.140
And I thought I'd have to
log on and answer them.

00:41:41.140 --> 00:41:44.040
But before I can even log on,
somebody else has answered

00:41:44.040 --> 00:41:46.090
them and they've given
a really good answer.

00:41:46.090 --> 00:41:49.540
And so it seems like a very
lively place and a lot of

00:41:49.540 --> 00:41:51.250
participation.

00:41:51.250 --> 00:41:55.520
So that seems very satisfying,
until you do the math.

00:41:55.520 --> 00:41:58.730
When you say out of all of the
