00:46:40.880 --> 00:46:43.820
So we're not forcing them
to do anything.

00:46:43.820 --> 00:46:46.010
They haven't paid any money
for these classes.

00:46:46.010 --> 00:46:47.810
They could drop out
at any time.

00:46:47.810 --> 00:46:49.610
So the fact that they don't
drop out means this is

00:46:49.610 --> 00:46:51.600
something they really
wanted to do.

00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:54.640
But they needed the motivational
structure to

00:46:54.640 --> 00:46:58.030
figure out when to do it
and when to fit it in.

00:46:58.030 --> 00:47:02.830
And the benefit of having the
due date is now when you go

00:47:02.830 --> 00:47:05.800
into the discussion forum, you
get an answer right away.

00:47:05.800 --> 00:47:07.850
Because everybody
else is online

00:47:07.850 --> 00:47:09.120
working on the same thing.

00:47:13.900 --> 00:47:17.110
So I somewhat sympathize with
this idea that it's a false

00:47:17.110 --> 00:47:18.450
motivation.

00:47:18.450 --> 00:47:21.920
But there's also a real
motivation of camaraderie, of

00:47:21.920 --> 00:47:24.440
saying we're all in this
together and we're

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:26.620
doing it right now.

00:47:26.620 --> 00:47:29.250
And I think that part
is genuine.

00:47:29.250 --> 00:47:33.190
Now, can you have it so that
we don't need any of these

00:47:33.190 --> 00:47:36.140
dates and people just want
to come back and

00:47:36.140 --> 00:47:36.960
do it on their own?

00:47:36.960 --> 00:47:38.210
And people talk about that.

00:47:38.210 --> 00:47:41.370
There's talk about
gamification.

00:47:41.370 --> 00:47:44.010
If people are so excited about
playing video games and they

00:47:44.010 --> 00:47:48.010
don't need due dates to play a
video game, can we do the same

00:47:48.010 --> 00:47:50.120
for education?

00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:53.120
I think that's worth trying
to understand better.

00:47:57.408 --> 00:48:02.030
And people talk about putting
in all these badges and

00:48:02.030 --> 00:48:03.300
points and so on.

00:48:03.300 --> 00:48:05.220
And people get motivation
for that.

00:48:05.220 --> 00:48:08.460
That's a little bit different
than due dates, but it's also

00:48:08.460 --> 00:48:11.390
external rather than internal.

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:15.290
I think the reason people get
excited by video games is

00:48:15.290 --> 00:48:18.220
because they're doing something
that's epic.

00:48:18.220 --> 00:48:22.840
So it's not that you get the
badge, it's that, hey, I saved

00:48:22.840 --> 00:48:24.080
the world from aliens.

00:48:24.080 --> 00:48:26.250
How cool is that?

00:48:26.250 --> 00:48:29.270
Yeah, I do realize they
weren't real aliens.

00:48:29.270 --> 00:48:32.350
But it's the fact that I
participated in something

00:48:32.350 --> 00:48:34.940
great that keeps me coming
back to want to

00:48:34.940 --> 00:48:35.860
play the video game.

00:48:35.860 --> 00:48:39.030
I think we have to make
education like that.

00:48:39.030 --> 00:48:43.160
And I think part of it is having
them do real stuff.

00:48:43.160 --> 00:48:46.020
So I said education is about
you doing something rather

00:48:46.020 --> 00:48:48.070
than listening to something.

00:48:48.070 --> 00:48:50.640
And if we make you build
something cool, then I think

00:48:50.640 --> 00:48:52.170
people will want to come
back and do it.

00:48:52.170 --> 00:48:55.740
I think they get turned off when
they say I have to answer

00:48:55.740 --> 00:48:58.820
a question about this train's
going 10 miles an hour and the

00:48:58.820 --> 00:49:00.740
other train's going
20 miles per hour.

00:49:00.740 --> 00:49:04.600
And when I'm done, I haven't
accomplished anything.

00:49:04.600 --> 00:49:07.470
I know everyone's done that
problem before and I'm not

00:49:07.470 --> 00:49:10.100
proud of having done it.

00:49:10.100 --> 00:49:13.400
But if we can give them things
where at the end, hey, I built

00:49:13.400 --> 00:49:14.500
something that's really cool.

00:49:14.500 --> 00:49:16.830
That I can share with my friends
and that I can be

00:49:16.830 --> 00:49:20.440
proud of having built, then I
think you'll get people coming

00:49:20.440 --> 00:49:21.880
back for the intrinsic reason.

00:49:24.562 --> 00:49:26.100
AUDIENCE: Hello, my
name is Josiah.

00:49:26.100 --> 00:49:30.070
I work as a professor at the
University of Paris.

00:49:30.070 --> 00:49:32.540
Aren't you a bit afraid
of something?

00:49:32.540 --> 00:49:35.720
The humanity has proven to be
able to keep books on shelves

00:49:35.720 --> 00:49:38.110
for hundreds of years.

00:49:38.110 --> 00:49:41.390
It has also proven to be able
to lose, for instance, the

00:49:41.390 --> 00:49:43.400
source code of [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:43.400 --> 00:49:45.800
40 years ago.

00:49:45.800 --> 00:49:50.420
Aren't you a bit afraid to see
all this material lost?

00:49:50.420 --> 00:49:54.790
And maybe with these kind of
tools we are building a new,

00:49:54.790 --> 00:49:59.230
great Library of Alexandria
that is bound to disappear

00:49:59.230 --> 00:50:03.930
with all those wonderful things
that has been lost.

00:50:03.930 --> 00:50:05.840
PETER NORVIG: Yeah, so that's
a great question.

00:50:05.840 --> 00:50:09.640
Now, of course, the Library of
Alexandria didn't fare so

00:50:09.640 --> 00:50:10.490
well, either.

00:50:10.490 --> 00:50:14.500
So centralizing all your
paper in one place

00:50:14.500 --> 00:50:17.610
is not a good strategy.

00:50:17.610 --> 00:50:20.500
So it's better to have it
decentralized and stored in

00:50:20.500 --> 00:50:21.520
many places.

00:50:21.520 --> 00:50:24.250
It's also good to have it stored
in a format that's

00:50:24.250 --> 00:50:25.350
going to persist.

00:50:25.350 --> 00:50:28.240
And so why would this
fail to persist?

00:50:28.240 --> 00:50:31.480
Well, one reason would be
that formats change.

00:50:31.480 --> 00:50:37.320
So whether it's a physical
format, it was on a USB drive

00:50:37.320 --> 00:50:40.200
and we moved on and we don't
have USB drives anymore.

00:50:40.200 --> 00:50:41.570
That would be a problem.

00:50:41.570 --> 00:50:45.300
I think that's becoming less of
a problem as we have these

00:50:45.300 --> 00:50:47.615
cloud services and things are
reproduced everywhere.

00:50:47.615 --> 00:50:50.350
And you don't worry so much
about the physical format.

00:50:50.350 --> 00:50:54.700
So then it becomes more
the data format of,

00:50:54.700 --> 00:50:56.740
is this going to--

00:50:56.740 --> 00:51:00.900
standards going to change and
JPEGs, or movies, or whatever,

00:51:00.900 --> 00:51:03.570
are no longer needed.

00:51:03.570 --> 00:51:05.960
I guess there you just need

00:51:05.960 --> 00:51:08.180
documentation of past standards.

00:51:08.180 --> 00:51:10.100
That will live for a while.

00:51:10.100 --> 00:51:13.570
I don't know if the JPEG
standard is going to be used a

00:51:13.570 --> 00:51:17.230
hundred years from now, but I'm
pretty sure if a hundred

00:51:17.230 --> 00:51:20.690
years from now you gave me
a JPEG, I could find the

00:51:20.690 --> 00:51:22.780
definition of what it
was like and write

00:51:22.780 --> 00:51:24.840
a translation program.

00:51:24.840 --> 00:51:26.130
So I'm not so worried
about that.

00:51:26.130 --> 00:51:28.990
And then the other thing to
worry about is the end of

00:51:28.990 --> 00:51:30.310
civilization.

00:51:30.310 --> 00:51:35.070
If there is no electricity, then
I can't run this program.

00:51:35.070 --> 00:51:38.090
Whereas, like the paper stuff
would probably still persist.

00:51:38.090 --> 00:51:40.730
And I guess we should
worry about that.

00:51:40.730 --> 00:51:41.730
But if that happens,
we got bigger

00:51:41.730 --> 00:51:43.988
problems to worry about.

00:51:43.988 --> 00:51:47.327
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:51:47.327 --> 00:51:49.010
AUDIENCE: Hi, my name's Dylan.

00:51:49.010 --> 00:51:52.110
I used to be a teaching
assistant at Tech for a really

00:51:52.110 --> 00:51:55.400
long time, teaching computing
to engineers or people who

00:51:55.400 --> 00:51:57.970
weren't specifically in the
study of computing.

00:51:57.970 --> 00:52:01.140
And you talked a lot about how
we can use computing to make

00:52:01.140 --> 00:52:02.620
education better.

00:52:02.620 --> 00:52:04.910
But what are the things we can
do to make education of

00:52:04.910 --> 00:52:08.640
computing better, especially in
our younger age groups or

00:52:08.640 --> 00:52:10.230
with female demographics?

00:52:10.230 --> 00:52:11.400
PETER NORVIG: Yeah.

00:52:11.400 --> 00:52:15.303
I think there's a lot of
efforts there now.

00:52:15.303 --> 00:52:19.100
And I guess keep experimenting
is the right way to do it.

00:52:22.350 --> 00:52:23.470
Figure out what works.

00:52:23.470 --> 00:52:26.190
Figure out, are there
things that are

00:52:26.190 --> 00:52:28.080
intimidating certain groups?

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:30.870
Are we doing things wrong so
that we're excluding part of

00:52:30.870 --> 00:52:32.330
the population?

00:52:32.330 --> 00:52:35.460
I think also some of it is
that it's just hard.

00:52:38.440 --> 00:52:42.400
I ran into Don Knuth recently
at an event.

00:52:42.400 --> 00:52:45.720
And he had famously said that
he thought that only 2% of

00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:47.890
people could be programmers.

00:52:47.890 --> 00:52:53.070
And I asked him if he still
thought that and he said yes.

00:52:53.070 --> 00:52:56.600
But I think maybe his standards
are just too high.

00:52:56.600 --> 00:53:00.640
Because if you think of,
well, how many people

00:53:00.640 --> 00:53:03.500
can play the piano.

00:53:03.500 --> 00:53:05.840
Is the answer 2% or is
it something else?

00:53:05.840 --> 00:53:07.370
Well, it depends on what
you mean right.

00:53:07.370 --> 00:53:11.830
So I can play "Chopsticks."
Alfred can

00:53:11.830 --> 00:53:13.350
play the piano well.

00:53:13.350 --> 00:53:18.750
And other people can be
a symphony player.

00:53:18.750 --> 00:53:22.530
And where do you draw the line
between who is a piano player

00:53:22.530 --> 00:53:23.460
and who isn't?

00:53:23.460 --> 00:53:27.450
So I think we can get a lot more
than 2% up to the sort of

00:53:27.450 --> 00:53:31.680
core competency of, yes, I can
bang out a tune, even if I'm

00:53:31.680 --> 00:53:34.970
never going to be a professional
at it.

00:53:34.970 --> 00:53:38.020
And maybe we should put more of
our focus on that, rather

00:53:38.020 --> 00:53:42.970
than just saying, can we hire
more people to have this as a

00:53:42.970 --> 00:53:43.910
professional job?

00:53:43.910 --> 00:53:47.370
I'd rather focus on, can we get
more people having a basic

00:53:47.370 --> 00:53:49.635
understanding, so that they can
apply that to the rest of

00:53:49.635 --> 00:53:50.490
their life?

00:53:50.490 --> 00:53:53.270
And there, I think it's got
to be a lot more than 2%.

00:53:53.270 --> 00:53:56.390
I don't know if it's 50%,
or 80%, or 95%.

00:53:56.390 --> 00:54:00.430
But I think we can get most
of the people there.

00:54:00.430 --> 00:54:02.600
And I guess we're going
to have to stop now.

00:54:02.600 --> 00:54:03.600
I'm sorry, we don't have time
for more questions.

00:54:03.600 --> 00:54:09.887
[APPLAUSE]

